---
import FrameworkLayout from '../../layouts/FrameworkLayout.astro';
import { url } from '../../utils';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "MedicalWebPage",
  "name": "Phase 4: Sustainment — Hospital Acupuncture Implementation",
  "description": "Normalise acupuncture and acupressure into routine hospital practice through leadership, fidelity monitoring, staffing support, and ongoing funding strategies.",
  "url": "https://hospitalacupuncture.com/framework/sustainment/",
  "lastReviewed": "2026-04",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Dr Zhen Zheng",
    "affiliation": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "RMIT University" }
  }
};
---

<FrameworkLayout
  title="Sustainment"
  description="Normalise acupuncture and acupressure into routine hospital practice so the intervention persists beyond the implementation team."
  phaseNumber={4}
  bottomLine="Implementations often fail after the project team moves on. Sustainability depends on normalising practices into routine operations — making them 'just how we do things here.' This requires ongoing attention to both outer factors (external leadership, inter-organisational links, funding) and inner factors (fidelity, staffing, coaching)."
  schema={schema}
>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The most common failure mode in hospital innovation is not failed implementation &mdash;
    it is failed sustainment. Programmes that were running well can quietly fade once the
    initial champions move on, funding cycles end, or staff turn over.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sustainment depends on normalising the acupuncture/acupressure intervention into routine
    operations and ensuring it continues to meet organisational needs. This requires attention
    to both outer (external) and inner (organisational) factors.
  </p>

  <!-- Outer Factors -->
  <h2>Outer Factors</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>External Leadership</summary>
    <p>
      External leadership support &mdash; from government bodies, professional associations,
      or health department directives &mdash; can significantly bolster sustainment. When
      acupuncture/acupressure is endorsed or recommended in external guidelines, it provides
      institutional legitimacy that outlasts any individual champion.
    </p>
    <p>Actions to strengthen external leadership support:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Align your programme with national or state-level clinical guidelines</li>
      <li>Seek endorsement from relevant professional bodies</li>
      <li>Publish outcomes to contribute to the broader evidence base</li>
      <li>Present at conferences to build peer recognition</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Links to Other Organisations</summary>
    <p>
      When peer hospitals are implementing similar practices, it creates constructive pressure
      to sustain your own programme. Organisational networks also provide shared learning,
      troubleshooting support, and collective advocacy.
    </p>
    <p>Strategies:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Connect with other hospitals that have implemented acupuncture/acupressure</li>
      <li>Join or establish an implementation network or community of practice</li>
      <li>Share outcomes, protocols, and training materials across organisations</li>
      <li>Participate in collaborative research or multi-site audits</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Funding</summary>
    <p>
      Long-term funding is a critical determinant of sustainment. The key question is whether
      acupuncture/acupressure can be demonstrated to be cost-neutral or cost-saving compared
      to existing practice.
    </p>
    <p>Consider:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Is the intervention cost-neutral when reductions in rescue medication and recovery
        time are factored in?</li>
      <li>Can consumable costs (wristbands, needles) be absorbed into existing budgets?</li>
      <li>Are there grant or quality improvement funding streams that support ongoing delivery?</li>
      <li>Can patient outcome improvements (shorter stays, fewer complications) be translated
        into a business case for ongoing investment?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>PONV example:</strong> Acupressure wristbands cost ~$5 AUD per patient. If they
      reduce rescue antiemetic use (RR 0.62) and contribute to shorter recovery room stays,
      the intervention may be cost-saving overall.
    </p>
  </details>

  <!-- Inner Factors -->
  <h2>Inner Factors</h2>

  <details open>
    <summary>Organisational Leadership</summary>
    <p>
      Internal leadership support must be cultivated from Phase 1 onward and actively maintained
      during sustainment. Key strategies:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Regular audit reports to leadership</strong> &mdash; keep the programme visible
        in organisational reporting. Out of sight is out of mind.</li>
      <li><strong>Align outcomes with organisational mission</strong> &mdash; frame acupuncture/acupressure
        outcomes in terms leadership cares about: patient experience scores, complication rates,
        length of stay, innovation reputation.</li>
      <li><strong>Leadership engagement from the start</strong> &mdash; leaders who were involved
        in the decision to implement are more likely to sustain support.</li>
      <li><strong>Succession planning</strong> &mdash; ensure that when key leaders move on,
        their successors understand and support the programme.</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Fidelity</summary>
    <p>
      Fidelity refers to whether the intervention continues to be delivered as intended.
      Over time, practices can drift &mdash; sometimes subtly &mdash; reducing effectiveness.
    </p>
    <h4>Common Fidelity Issues</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Wristband displacement below the correct PC6 location</li>
      <li>Shortened treatment duration as staff become casual about timing</li>
      <li>Incomplete documentation making outcomes untrackable</li>
      <li>New staff delivering the intervention without adequate training</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>Strategies to Maintain Fidelity</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Onsite monitoring and regular observational audits</li>
      <li>Staff feedback loops &mdash; ask practitioners what difficulties they encounter</li>
      <li>Visible, accessible education materials at point of care (posters, laminated guides)</li>
      <li>Regular education sessions aligned with routine practice protocols (e.g., annual
        competency reviews)</li>
      <li>Periodic re-assessment using the audit tools from Phase 3</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Staffing and Support Coaching</summary>
    <p>
      Staff turnover is the greatest threat to sustainment. New staff who were not part of the
      original implementation may not understand why the intervention exists or how to deliver
      it correctly.
    </p>
    <h4>Strategies</h4>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Detail</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Unit-level champions</strong></td>
          <td>Identify an enthusiastic champion in each work unit who can onboard new staff,
            answer questions, and maintain momentum.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Manager reminders</strong></td>
          <td>Include acupuncture/acupressure in regular management communications &mdash;
            team meetings, handover protocols, quality dashboards.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Accessible education materials</strong></td>
          <td>Keep training resources visible and easy to find. Laminated point-of-care guides,
            intranet pages, and QR codes linking to video tutorials.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Orientation integration</strong></td>
          <td>Add acupuncture/acupressure to new staff orientation programmes so it is
            learned as a standard part of practice from day one.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ongoing education</strong></td>
          <td>Schedule regular refresher sessions matching the frequency of other mandatory
            clinical education (e.g., annual skills updates).</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>

  <!-- Sustainment Checklist -->
  <h2>Sustainment Self-Check</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Is Your Programme Sustainable? Key Questions</summary>
    <p>Use these questions for periodic self-assessment:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Domain</th><th>Question</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Leadership</td>
          <td>Does current leadership actively support the programme?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Funding</td>
          <td>Is the programme funded through a sustainable budget line?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Fidelity</td>
          <td>Are recent audits showing the intervention is delivered correctly?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Staffing</td>
          <td>Do new staff receive training as part of orientation?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Documentation</td>
          <td>Are outcomes still being tracked and reported?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>External support</td>
          <td>Is the intervention included in current clinical guidelines?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Patient experience</td>
          <td>Are patients still being offered the intervention consistently?</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      If the answer to any of these questions is "no" or "I don't know," that domain needs
      attention to prevent programme erosion.
    </p>
  </details>

